               <interp inst="t18420613-2012" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18420613"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18420613-2012" type="date" value="18420613"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18420613-2012-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-2012-18420613 t18420613-2012-offence-1 t18420613-2012-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>2012. <persName id="def1-2012-18420613" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-2012-18420613" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2012-18420613" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-2012-18420613" type="given" value="ADOLPHUS FREDERICK"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ADOLPHUS FREDERICK TAYLOR</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18420613-2012-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18420613-2012-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18420613-2012-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18420613-cd-267" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420613-2012-offence-1 t18420613-cd-267"></join>25th of May</rs>, 27 tassels, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 288 buttons, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 11 caps, value 19<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; 6 yards of printed cotton, value 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.; 54 yards of ribbon, value 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 3/4 of a yard of velvet, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18420613-name-1479" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1479" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1479" type="surname" value="MULLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1479" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1479" type="occupation" value="Japan hat and cap manufacturers"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18420613-2012-offence-1 t18420613-name-1479"></join>William Muller</persName> and another, his masters.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1480" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1480" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1480" type="surname" value="MULLER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1480" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM MULLER</persName>
                  </hi> I am in partnership with Mr. Simpson—we are Japan hat and cap manufacturers, in Farnham-place, South wark—we have be<lb></lb>tween seventy and eighty persons in our employ. The prisoner was foreman of the cap department, and had been so about seven months—he kept a shop of his own in the London-road—he dealt with us for Japan hats, but never for caps, or buttons, or velvet—on Sunday, the 15th of May, in conse<lb></lb>quence of suspicion, I marked a quantity of tassels, ribbons, and chene velvet, and packets of buttons, in the gross packets—I afterwards missed some packets of buttons, and twenty-four inches of two pieces of this vel<lb></lb>vet—here is a pattern of it—it is a cotton velvet, not very valuable—this piece was found at the prisoner's house, and this is the piece it was cut from—the prisoner was taken into custody on the 27th of May—I accom<lb></lb>panied the officer to search his house, and found these three gross packets of buttons—I can swear to two of them, from having the mark I put on them for detection—the other packet I believe to be ours, from its being a Kind of button not generally used in caps, but we bought it as a job—we found</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130242"></xptr>
               <p>nine tassels, the whole of which belongs to us—there is a pencil mark a the button of each, which is covered by the silk (they were marked as Sunday, the 15th) and some ribbons, one of the ribbons has not ur mart on it—the only reason I have to suppose it is ours, is that we bought what we call four pieces, and we never used a whole piece—we used a portions of a piece, and one piece is gone—we never sell ribbons, except made up; nor tassels, but as forming part of a cap; nor valve, except made up—we found some caps—they are not marked, but from the particular quality of the cloth, and their appearance, I have no doubt they an ours—I believe all these caps have had our stamp taken. off then—it was a paper stamp stuck on with gum—when we took them, one of them had our stamp it, but before we left his premises his wife concealed it—I saw it, and called the attention of the inspector to it, but it was taken away—the stuff of these caps is particular—it was made by brother for shipment, but it was not ready when his other goods were, and we bought it of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When the prisoner was first engaged I suppose you made some inquiries? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> We understood he had been living with Mr. Wilson, with our foreman, Mr. Hunt, had been living—we were satisfied with Mr. Hunt's representation, we had that confidence in him and we knew the prisoner was in business on opinion of his abilities—I do not know that he has the character of a first rate hand—the time he devoted to our services at first was from nine o'clock in the morning till one—we afterwards came to an arrangement for him to give us his time from nine till five o'clock, for which we paid him 30<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a week—we proposed that he should give up his wholesale trade, a proposed he should give up his business entirely—I never did so—Mr. Simpon might have done so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you not propose that he should give up his business entirely, and devote the whole of his time to your business, and bind himself in as agreement not to enter into any other person's employ for six months? No—we proposed he should give up his wholesale business, and enter into an agreement of 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., not to enter not any other persons employ, but I do not think by my partner—the prisoner rather agreed to the proposal that he should give up his wholesale business, but the thing was never brought to a conclusion—it was only talked of—O swear he did not refuse to did it—the proposal was made two or three months ago—he carried on the same business as us—he sold the same sorts of hats and caps—I knew where he lived—it was within half a mile of or shop—I went to his shop once before—I think it was before he was in our employ—to the best of my recollection, I never was in his shop again, till we went to search his place—I think about thirty or forty men work on run premises, they are only hat makers—we employ a good many women—the prisoner employed some of the same women as employ a good many women—the prisoner employed some of the same women as we did—they worked at home whether for us or him—among them is in person named Mrs. Carpenter—since I gave the prisoner into custody, I have had some conversation with her—i selected the nine tassels, I found at the prisoner's house from about two</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130243"></xptr>
               <p>dozen caps—a person employed by the prisoner brought them In—they were it two bags—they were on the caps—I did not claim any of the caps—they were made by Mrs. Carpenter—I hare had conversation with her about caps—at the time I found these caps she was at work for us—two young girls in Mrs. Carpenter's employ brought home these two dozen caps—I do not know their names, or where they lived—they have not been in my employ, that I am aware of—I never saw them before—I had this conversation with Mrs. Carpenter on the Monday morning after—she told me the had made these Gaps for the prisoner, and a great many others—I do not think she told me she made three dozen at the tame time—I will not swear she did not—she said she had some caps to make for us at the same time, and she had put on three of our tassels in mistake for the prisoner's—she did not say nine—she is still in our service.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Having ascertained this, why have you indicted him for stealing sine, when she had put three on in mistake? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I had not ascertained that it the time of his commitment—I have preferred this indictment within the last three or four days—he was in the habit of cutting out at my premises—that was his principal work—I never knew of his bring<lb></lb>ing bit own materials to our shop to cut out—I have since understood that be has given his own materials to the workwomen who worked there—he has never bought any materials of us for cap-making—Mr. Sinpson is in the habit of selling in our shop sometime, and Hunt like wise, and they are all—Hunt keeps the day-book—it is his duty to enter in the books the goods he sells in the course of the day—Hunt has been in our service about fourteen months, and is so still-I have had no dis<lb></lb>pots with Hunt lately—I thought it necessary to call on him for an expla<lb></lb>nation of his conduct—he had the management of my petty cash up to about March—I have relieved him from that part "of his duty—I swear to the best of my belief about these caps—I saw these five the first time I went to the prisoner's shop—I looked at them, and said I believed they were ours—I left them behind me, because I did not know I had a right to take them—I took what I could swear to—I saw this piece of ribbon the first time I went—I examined it, and left it behind—there were some labels taken—they are about 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a thousand—I never borrowed any labels from the prisoner to my knowledge—Mr. Simpson is on a journey—he was not at home when I went to the prisoner's house—I bought this even velvet at Capper's wholesale warehouse, in Old change—they sup<lb></lb>ply persons in our line—I have never seen any of this velvet it the trade, but what we have—it may be about three months since I bought it—these buttons are commonly used it that business—I went on a Friday to the prisoner's house—I found these things behind the counter, mixed up in<lb></lb>discriminately with other goods—Mrs. Taylor was in the shop—no one else—we found one cap with one of our tickets in—I handed it to the inspector, and said, "I will swear to that"—he laid it down, and we looked all about the shop afterwards, and could not find it—there was only a lit<lb></lb>tle boy there—Mrs. Taylor was seen to touch the parcel—I did not see her touch the cap.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did the prisoner's attorney come to you to sub<lb></lb>pcena some persons? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I called the parties before him—I have brought all my books in obedience to his directions—these two gross of buttons have the mark I put on them on Sunday—I never sold them or</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130244"></xptr>
               <p>handed them to any one to make up—they are taken out fa one a two dozens as they are wanted—there were no other tassels besides these nine—his were a great deal worse.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1481" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1481" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1481" type="surname" value="BALLARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1481" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN BALLARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of William Ballard, who was formerlys policeman, and live in Chapel-place. On Saturday the 21st of May, in co. sequence of an arrangement, I went to the prisoner's shop in the London road—I bought a cap there, and said I wished to have a baby's'-l said I wished to make a present to a little boy of a cap, to go out of doors, and wanted a very pretty one made"—the prisoner asked if I should like one of cheni velvet—he showed me a bit of ribbon of the colour and I ordered him to make one by Wednesday—I deposited 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>—be said he had not got one by him, but would have one made for me—on Wed nesday the 23rd I went to the shop and received this cap—(<hi rend="italic">producing it</hi>)—I paid 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I did not see him the day I got the cap—I went the next day, and saw him, and said the cap was too large—I wanted a smaller one—he said he would make me one, and would take this back if it did not suit me—I said the child was small, I would keep it, and he might make me another of the same colour—he said he had not sufficient vel<lb></lb>vet—he bought but a small piece in the market, and if he had to buy more the cap might not be so cheap.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CHARNOCK</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You did not get the second cap? A No—I went to the shop because I was told to do so by my hus<lb></lb>band—I was by myself when he bid me—I did not see any one else-I had no communication with the prosecutor about this cap—I did not give the measure—I told the child's age—I had taken this cap home and tried it on—I did not return it because I thought it was cheap, and I could give it to a child—there was no other reason for my wanting another—my husband told me not to take it back—I live in an ordinary sized house-we keep baths.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1482" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1482" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1482" type="surname" value="TOYNE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1482" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>JANE TOYNE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Lemon-street, Gravel-lane, and am in the em<lb></lb>ploy of Muller and Simpson. On Monday, the 23rd of May, I saw the prisoner at Mr. Muller's warehouse—he wished me to make a cap of the chain velvet—he intended purchasing a yard from Mr. Muller's—on the Wednesday he gave me the velvet—I made it up, and sent it to his house—this is it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you worked for Muller and Simpson? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About seventeen weeks—I work at home-I never saw the prisoner till I went to work for them—he was employed there cutting out—I do not know whether he brought his own materials from his shop and cut them out there—I once had a silk velvet cap of him at Mr. Muller's—he gave me the materials at Mr. Muller's warehouse to make it—he must have brought them from home—I once fetched a piece of cloth from the prisoner's to make a cap for the prosecutors—I never fetched any thing else—no one was present when he told me he should want me to make up a cap—I made no secret of it—I made it at my own house—I sent it to his own shop—I did not show it to any one.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1483" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1483" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1483" type="surname" value="HUNT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1483" type="given" value="EDWIN"></interp>EDWIN HUNT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am warehouseman to Muller and Simpson. It is my business to make the entries in the day-book—if the prisoner had made any purchase of any velvet or any materials to be made up at our shop, it would be my duty to enter it in the book—he made no purchase of any velvet of me—Mr. Muller occasionally makes entries, and Mr.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130245"></xptr>
               <p>Simpson—I never knew my master sell any velvet unprepared, nor any tassels or buttons.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you known the prisoner? A Some two or three years—I knew him in Mr. Wilson's service—I was also in Mr. Wilson's service—he has always borne the character of a respectable man, and been a first-rate man in his business—he was in Mr. Wilson's service when I went, and I left him there—he had the management of their cap business—he at that time carried on busi<lb></lb>ness for himself in the London-road—he worked on Muiler and Simpson's premises—I never recollect his bringing his own materials to make up—I remember some braid being fetched from his premises, which was made up for Muiler and Simpson, and we had some old hat-boxes of the prisoner—I have sold the prisoner an article we call" threshers," what the country farmer boys wear—I do not recollect any thing else—there was a cap or<lb></lb>dered of me—I ordered it of Simpson and Muiler, and the person did not call for it—I could not afford to lose it, and the prisoner took it of me—I was examined at the police-office—I swear I never sold, the prisoner any thing else—he never supplied the prosecutors with any buttons—I know that he employed some of the same workwomen as the prosecutors did—I swear positively I have never seen him giving them work to do for himself on the prosecutors' premises—there is a boy named William Trimm in the prosecutors' employ—he might look out hats for the prisoner, not caps and velvet—I think the prosecutors bought the chain velvet at Man<lb></lb>chester—I do not recollect whether they deal with any one in the Old Change—I do not know the value of the velvet—it is my duty to enter articles which I sell of the prosecutors—Messrs. Muiler and Simpson sometimes make entries of the articles they sell—the prosecutors are not in the habit of selling. materials to their workpeople—we have never done so—I told the prosecutors of the cap the prisoner ordered, on the day of his commitment—I told Mrs. Harris, the forewoman, I wanted a cap of a certain size, and she got it made for me—I paid the prosecutors for it—the prisoner made some allusion to a cap, and I said the only cap I sold him was the one I had entered—I entered it at the time I bought it, before I had it away from the premises, after I had ordered it—I left Mr. Wilson's employ about eighteen months ago—I had been in his service three years—I collected orders for him, and occasionally received cash—I left him suddenly—I was out of employ six months before I got to the prosecu<lb></lb>tors'—Mr. Gibbs, Mr. Wilson's partner, gave me a character to the prose<lb></lb>cuton—I swear I referred to them for a character—I had a dispute with Mr. Wilson before I left, about money matters—he was my partner at that time—I swear that Mr. Gibbs was not partner with me, but he was with Mr. Wilson—I was in business in Castle-street, Southwark, as a hat-manu<lb></lb>facturer, and Mr. Wilson was my partner there—"Edwin Hunt" was over the door—Mr. Wilson's name did not appear—his partnership with Mr. Gibbs was not made public, and mine with Mr. Wilson was not made pub<lb></lb>lic—I was in partnership with Wilson—our term was seven years—the business did not answer—Mr. Wilson got the money—there were deeds and an agreement—I left Mr. Wilson because he charged me with misappro<lb></lb>priating his money—I am not aware of the amount—it might be 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I left him the next day—I had been two years in his employ, receiving no salary—I was his partner and his servant—I have not taken any proceed<lb></lb>ings against Mr. Wilson to enforce my partnership agreement—I at one</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130246"></xptr>
               <p>time kept the prosecutors' petty cash—I have discontinued keeping it for six weeks or two months—a young man keeps it now—I have not had any dispute with the prosecutors about the petty cash—there have been errors, but no misappropriation—I have had no dispute with them about those errors—they were satisfied with my explanation—there was a dispute about 8l. which I was short in my account—I kept the petty cash for months after that—I have 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a week—I have never been charged with being drunk since I have been there—I have not got drunk on the pre<lb></lb>mises.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you ever charged with dishonesty by the prosecutors? A No—I did not run away when Mr. Wilson charged me with misappropriating his monies.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1484" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1484" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1484" type="surname" value="JARVIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1484" type="given" value="ELEANOR"></interp>ELEANOR JARVIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I made caps for the prosecutors—I receive the materials for doing so before I make them—I made part of these caps which were found at the prisoner's, for the prosecutors—I made part of this cap—I got the materials from the warehouse, and for these three also. <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long have you worked for the prosecutors? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About seventeen weeks—all that time the prisoner was there as foreman—I have made two caps for him at two different times—they were delivered at his premises—he delivered the materials to me to make them at the prosecutors' warehouse—a girl made the other part of these caps—I know I made them for the prosecutors by the work that is in them—the inside work is mine—I know it by the sewing of the lining—I have worked for other people besides—I have not made caps of this description for other people—they are of a different shape—I swear there is some of my work in this cap—the inside work of the top is mine, covered by the lining—it is called stitching in the top—I cannot see it-whether the work of other persons is like this or not I cannot tell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is this the form of cap you received to make A Yes, my work in this cap is under the lining—here is my work-I put the peak on this cap—the work on it is such as to enable me to say it is mine—I made two caps for the prisoner on two occasions, and be gave me the materials at the prosecutor's warehouse, but they were quite differ<lb></lb>ent to these—I have a book in which the prisoner writes the goods which I am to be paid for making up—part of this book is in Mr. Taylor's hand writing—I find in it the making up of two of the caps I made for the pri<lb></lb>soner on the 4th of April, and the two others, which I made on the 9th of May—the prisoner put "paid" to the book—none of them were made for the prosecutors—they were paid for at the prosecutors' warehouse by Mr. Mullins or Mr. Simpson.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18420613-name-1485" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1485" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1485" type="surname" value="MASON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18420613-name-1485" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MASON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am police-inspector. On Friday, the 27th of May, I received charge of the prisoner on his leaving Mr. Mullins—I went and searched his shop in the London-road—I found there these ribbons, velvet slips, and parcels of buttons, in grosses—they had the marks on them at the time—also these tassels for caps, with the marks in pencil under them, and the four caps which have been identified by Jarvis—among the caps there was one with the prosecutors' label on—I put it in a paper parcel among some other things that he identified, at the corner of the shelf—I saw Mrs. Tay<lb></lb>lor put her hand on the parcel—I said, "Don't move the parcel "—some time after it was taken away altogether, and found at last under some things on the counter, but the cap with the label was gone.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184206130247"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. JONES</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What time did you go? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About half-past fife in the afternoon—the shop was open—I found the ribbons and buttons on a shelf, and the caps in different bags—the drawers were unlocked—two of these caps were in the window—I stated my business—Mrs. Taylor was agitated—she remained in the shop—I searched all her apartments—there were about forty dozen caps in the shop.'</p>
               <p>
